    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Body Fat Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        This body fat calculator uses the U.S. Navy circumference method to estimate your body fat percentage from simple tape-measure readings. Start by selecting your sex — this matters because the formula differs for men and women, and women require an additional hip measurement. Choose your unit system (metric or imperial), then enter your waist, neck, and height measurements. If you selected female, a hip measurement field will appear automatically. Results display instantly as you type, showing your estimated body fat percentage and the corresponding fitness category.
      </p>
      <p>
        Body fat percentage is one of the most meaningful indicators of physical fitness and health. Unlike BMI, which simply relates weight to height, body fat percentage tells you how much of your body mass is actually fat versus lean tissue. This distinction is critical for athletes, fitness enthusiasts, and anyone who wants a more nuanced understanding of their body composition than a scale alone can provide.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>The U.S. Navy Body Fat Method</h2>
      <p>
        Developed by the United States Navy for fitness assessments, this method estimates body fat using logarithmic equations based on circumference measurements and height. For men, the formula is: <strong>%BF = 86.010 x log10(waist - neck) - 70.041 x log10(height) + 36.76</strong>. For women, the formula is: <strong>%BF = 163.205 x log10(waist + hip - neck) - 97.684 x log10(height) - 78.387</strong>. All measurements should be in centimeters. The method is based on the principle that the ratio of certain body circumferences to height correlates predictably with body fat levels.
      </p>

      <h3>How to Take Accurate Measurements</h3>
      <p>
        Accuracy depends entirely on consistent measurement technique. Measure your <strong>waist</strong> at the navel for men, or at the narrowest point of the natural waist for women. Keep the tape horizontal and snug but not compressing the skin. Measure your <strong>neck</strong> just below the larynx (Adam's apple), with the tape sloping slightly downward toward the front. For women, measure your <strong>hips</strong> at the widest point of the buttocks. Take all measurements on bare skin, standing upright and relaxed. For best consistency, measure at the same time of day, ideally in the morning before eating.
      </p>

      <h3>Body Fat Categories and What They Mean</h3>
      <p>
        Body fat categories vary by sex because women naturally carry more essential fat for reproductive and hormonal functions. For men, essential fat is roughly 2-5%, with the athletic range at 6-13%, the fit range at 14-17%, and an acceptable range at 18-24%. Readings above 25% are generally classified as obese. For women, essential fat is approximately 10-13%, the athletic range is 14-20%, the fit range is 21-24%, and the acceptable range is 25-31%. Readings above 32% fall into the obese category. These ranges provide general guidance — optimal body fat depends on individual goals, age, and overall health.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How does the U.S. Navy body fat formula work?</h3>
      <p>
        The U.S. Navy method estimates body fat percentage using circumference measurements. For men, the formula uses waist, neck, and height measurements. For women, it adds a hip measurement. The formula applies logarithmic calculations to these measurements to estimate the percentage of body weight that is fat.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a healthy body fat percentage?</h3>
      <p>
        Healthy body fat ranges differ by sex. For men, 6-13% is considered athletic, 14-17% is fit, 18-24% is acceptable, and above 25% is obese. For women, 14-20% is athletic, 21-24% is fit, 25-31% is acceptable, and above 32% is obese. Essential fat is about 2-5% for men and 10-13% for women.
      </p>

      <h3>Is body fat percentage more useful than BMI?</h3>
      <p>
        Body fat percentage provides a more accurate picture of body composition than BMI because it directly estimates fat mass rather than simply relating weight to height. Two people can have the same BMI but very different body fat percentages depending on their muscle mass. Body fat percentage is especially useful for athletes and physically active individuals.
      </p>

      <h3>How accurate is the U.S. Navy body fat method?</h3>
      <p>
        The U.S. Navy method is accurate to within about 3-4% of body fat for most people when measurements are taken correctly. It is less accurate than DEXA scans or hydrostatic weighing but more accessible and free. Consistent measuring technique is key to getting reliable results.
      </p>

      <h3>How should I take body measurements for this calculator?</h3>
      <p>
        Measure your waist at the narrowest point (at the navel for men, at the narrowest point for women). Measure your neck just below the larynx (Adam's apple), sloping slightly downward at the front. Measure hips (women only) at the widest point of the buttocks. Use a flexible tape measure and keep it snug but not compressing the skin.
      </p>
    

